tual size—including the colossal seven-pound Goliath Frog. Accessibly written by expert Tim Halliday and containing the most up-to-date information, The Book of Frogs will captivate both veteran researchers and amateur herpetologists. As frogs increasingly make headlines for their troubling worldwide decline, the importance of these fascinating creatures to their ecosystems remains underappreciated. The Book of Frogs brings readers face to face with six hundred astonishingly unique and irreplaceable species that display a diverse array of adaptations to habitats that are under threat of destruction throughout the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aFrogsxAnatomy. 0aFrogsxBehavior. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  afrogs, amphibians, conservation, population, habitat, species, taxonomy, science, zoology, biology, toxins, tadpoles, breeding, reproduction, predation, defense, animal behavior, hibernation, distribution, herpetology, goliath, poison, darwin, toads, disease, nonfiction, reference, endangered, extinct, newly discovered, global diversity, ichthyology, naturalist.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226184791423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226184791/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles